div.p:
Blue carbon is defined as the organic carbon sequestered above and below the soil surface of coastal ecosystems (e.g., tidal marshes, mangroves, and halophytes) (Macreadie et al.

 2019

). Recently, the interest in blue carbon as a method to cope with global warming has increased world-wide. Attempts to manage, protect, and restore blue carbon habitats are underway as part of the policies developed to mitigate global carbon emissions (Howard et al.

 2017

; Siikamäki et al.

 2013

). Blue carbon has considerably higher carbon stocks than terrestrial ecosystems because it has been sequestered for thousands to millions of years in underlying plant sediments (Duarte et al.

 2005

; Lo Iacono et al.

 2008

). Blue carbon reservoirs are being continually destroyed because of various developmental activities (Wu et al.

 2020

), and if the destruction continues at the current rate, 30%–40% of the coastal wetlands are expected to disappear over the next 100 years (Pendleton et al.

 2012

).

If coastal wetlands are efficiently conserved, blue carbon reservoirs can be used to achieve the nationally determined contribution (NDC) target under the Paris agreement. To incorporate blue carbon into the NDC target, assessing the carbon stocks (total carbon stored in individual regions) and monitoring the changes in the greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions over time is essential. The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) provides Tier 1–3 monitoring, reporting, and verification (MRV) guidelines for national carbon stock, sources, and sinks, according to the level of detail and accuracy of blue carbon measurements (Hiraishi et al.

 2014

). The IPCC recommends that Tier 3 should consider the local specific characteristics of individual countries. Because various halophytes and soils constituting coastal wetlands have different amounts of carbon stocks, high implementation costs and technical skills are required to obtain and standardize blue carbon stock information under the IPCC Tier 3 (Park and Um

 2018

).

This study was conducted based on three different types of survey and analysis methods (Fig.

 1

); UAV remote sensing, field survey, and elemental analysis (EA). In the remote sensing step, the acquisition of UAV imagery, data preprocessing, and object-based image analysis and verification were conducted. The field survey was conducted using quadrat methods in random survey points. EA is used to derive organic carbon from dried-oven samples. The study area is located in Sinwol-ro, Goseong-eup, Goseong-gun, and Gyeongsangnam-do, South Korea (34° 56′52.18 N, 128° 20′23.06 E) (Fig.

 2

). This region has a favorable topographical condition for the development of coastal wetlands because the coastline is formed by several large and small inner bays with a major tidal current difference between that flowing seaward (ebb current) and inland (flood current). The experimental area has an excellent natural vegetation community in terms of biological diversity and richness because it is composed of various types of soil, such as sand, mud, and silt. Moreover, the area presents geographic features suitable for surveying the blue carbon accumulated in coastal wetlands.

UAV imagery was acquired in summer (August 29, 2020), when the solar zenith angle was at its highest (1:00 PM) to minimize the noise from the shadow and tide ebb. A DJI Matrice 200v2 was used as a platform to collect UAV imagery; it consists of a quadcopter with a maximum flight altitude of 3,000 m and maximum flight time of 30 min (Table

 1

). A DJI Zenmuse X4s camera was used for image acquisition, consisting of four wavelength ranges, i.e., blue, green, red, and near-infrared (NIR, 800–900 nm) spectrum. Using the Dronedeploy software (an autonomous flight software) connected to Google Maps, the flight altitude was set to 100 m, and the side and end lap were set to 75%. A total of 357 original images were automatically captured to ensure the uniform consistency and precision required to generate the orthophoto.

Agisoft PhotoScan was used to calculate three-dimensional (3D) information from overlapping images using the Structure-from-Motion (SfM) technique, which is an aerial photogrammetry algorithm. SfM generates a 3D point cloud by extracting 16 common feature points from multiple images without prior information regarding the camera parameters at the time of image acquisition (Verhoeven

 2011

). Raw UAV imagery was produced as an orthophoto using the SfM batch process function of the Agisoft PhotoScan (Fig.

 3

).

The field sampling method can be applied differently, depending on the accessibility of the study area; however, random sampling is generally recommended. The number of samples should be at least 2% of the total study area. Therefore, random sampling points (

 N

= 400) were generated on the map, and a quadrat (1 m × 1 m) survey was conducted, excluding the flooded area. A sample of the community included in the pixel size (3 cm × 3 cm) of UAV imagery was collected via subsampling in the field survey. The sample vegetation was dried at an oven heated to a temperature of 60 °C for 72 h to determine the biomass content (Howard et al.

 2014

). The biomass content (g px

 −1

) was calculated by measuring the dry mass of each sample and converted in each quadrat (1 m × 1 m) (Fig.

 4

). To calculate the carbon stock for a local specific target under the IPCC Tier 3 dimension, it was necessary to derive the carbon conversion factor for each plant species or soil (Hiraishi et al.

 2014

).

The elemental analysis (EA) is recommended as a standard method to measure blue carbon in coastal ecosystems by the Blue Carbon Initiative, International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) and Intergovernmental Oceanic Commission of UNESCO (Howard et al.

 2014

; IUCN

 2014

). In this study, the carbon conversion factor was derived

 by

employing an organic carbon analysis using the Flash 2000 elemental analyzer (ThermoFisher Scientific) for the on-site samples. The organic material sample was burned using a catalyst at a high-temperature induction furnace (approximately 950 °C), and the generated gas was separated using a gas chromatographic separation column. The carbon conversion factor was calculated based on the proportion of biomass composed of organic carbon. The equation for calculating the carbon stock was proposed by the Blue Carbon Initiative (Howard et al.

 2014

). Carbon stock was estimated by combining the classification results derived via UAV imagery with EA results, as shown below (Formula 1);

Distinguishing halophyte communities with reliable accuracy is crucial because it plays a key role in the quantitative evaluation of vegetative organic carbon. Upon implementing machine learning, verification of the accuracy of the classification model was required for the data set (Table

 3

). The overall accuracy was 93.25%, and the Kappa coefficient was 0.90. The model used for classification indicated a strong positive correlation of spatial significance. In this study, the accuracy was evaluated using the precision-recall method to verify the extent of halophyte communities. Precision (correctness) is used to correctly evaluate the true patterns predicted from the results and classified as the true class (Hossin and Sulaiman

 2015

). Recall (completeness) is used to evaluate the ratio of correctly classified results within the true class. F1-score (0–1) is a measure used to mix the precision and recall values, and it is the weighted harmonic average of the precision and recall values. In this work, the overall F1-score (0.59–0.99) was positive, but the range of values was differentiated, depending on the spatial characteristics (several communities are mixed without clear boundary near water bodies) of each class.

In remote sensing, flight altitude has a strong impact on the spatial resolution that determines whether a halophyte community can be classified as a specific type of species (Table

 4

). In the case of satellite images, it is very hard to obtain images with a spatial resolution sufficient in estimating carbon accumulated in specific species because they provide limited ground sampling distance (GSD) at an altitude of more than 700 km. The aerial photograph collected at lower altitudes is required to ensure spatial resolution to identify halophyte communities, creating problems with flight safety. Several countries have regulations regarding the lowest permitted flight altitude of aircraft. The Federal Aviation Administration is a government agency responsible for aviation safety in the United States. According to Sect. 91.119 of the General Operating and Flight Rules, manned aircraft is not allowed to fly at altitudes less than 300 m (1000 ft) above urban and residential areas and 150 m (500 ft) above non-crowded areas. Even if the low-altitude flight of manned aircraft is permitted, the speed of the aircraft (for example, Cruise speed of Cessna 208 Grand Caravan: 344 km/h) makes it virtually impossible to obtain images with a spatial resolution sufficient to track sub-centimeter-sized patches of halophyte community, due to image motion. From a temporal resolution perspective, the long orbital cycle of satellites and the flight schedule of manned aircraft highly dependent on weather conditions lead to an intrinsic uncertainty in securing carbon content of the halophyte community that varies greatly from season to season. The satellites and manned aircraft providing images at high altitudes are subject to atmospheric distortions caused by sea fog, coastal fog, clouds and dust, which are intensively generated in the coastal landscape.
